As a simple solution to making of quick selection tool might be using the existing [grabcut](https://github.com/opencv/opencv/blob/master/modules/imgproc/src/grabcut.cpp) from openCV. If you remove the initial rectangle drawing and mark all the pixels as probable background (GC_PR_BGD), then what you will be having a simple quick selection tool. But there will be some fluctuations (when users intend to change the selection locally, some parts of the selection far from the region of interest may also change). We eliminate the fluctuation effect by assuming that users only want to make a new selection adjacent to the brush. After the progressive labeling, the new selection may consist of several disconnected regions. We reject those regions that are not connected to the seed pixels. This can be implemented by a search algorithm like a BFS or DFS in trees:

```
list<pixels> pixels_in_component;
stack<pixels> neighbours;
neighbours.add(starting_point)

while not neightbours.empty:
   p = neighbours.pop();
   pixels_in_component.append(p) 
   for each adjacent pixel n of p:
     if mask_val == GC_FGD || mask_val == GC_PR_FGD:
         neighbours.append(n)
```
pixels_in_component will later contain all you connected pixels. 
To make the overall process quick and fast we can call the grabCut on the reduced/downsampled version of the image like downsampling a 24MP to 1 MP and then calling the grabCut and then upscaling the results. This will improve the speed and the process of selection will be handy.

