@fedelibre Using the Message-ID and In-Reply-To headers is a great textbook definition/specification of what should be a thread and should certainly be there as one way to group messages into a thread, but maybe not as the only one.  Neither users (as you rightfully state) nor systems emitting emails (the example I am using as it does not adhere to the In-Reply-To header as said header is not even present) nor email clients are perfect.  
In regards to email clients, I am personally jumping between Geary, Apple Mail on iOS and Gmail web client and all three (3) treat what constitutes a thread differently, with the Gmail web client applying the seemingly IMO best logic, it just feels right what it does.  It however goes beyond the strict definition of what makes up a thread of messages and that may result in some cases in downside effects as you correctly state (threading together different threads just because they happen to have the same subject may happen and may not be correct).  It can get complicated and complex to add to the threading logic, I agree, and not everyone will be happy with the result.  I think though that by only sticking to the spec will turn some users away from adopting Geary as their preferred email client because Geary's threading logic could be perceived as lacking beyond that of other email clients and just like I jump between email clients out of necessity during any given day, I would think that the usage of different email clients is very typical.
So maybe a compromise is to make threading beyond Message-ID and In-Reply-To a preference and give the user the ability to enable applying additional threading logic like 'threading by subject'.
